Yes ✅ — plain (vanilla) JavaScript can store and read cookies using document.cookie.
Below is a clear, practical guide with working examples, plus important security notes so you know what JS can and cannot do with cookies.

🍪 1. How Cookies Work in JavaScript (Basics)
	• Cookies are stored as key=value pairs
	• JavaScript accesses them via document.cookie
	• All cookies are stored as one string
	• JavaScript cannot access HttpOnly cookies

✅ 2. Store a Cookie (Plain JavaScript)
✅ Basic cookie

document.cookie = "username=Raja";
``
✔ Stored in browser
✔ Sent with every request to same domain

✅ Cookie with expiry

const expires = new Date();
expires.setDate(expires.getDate() + 7); // 7 days
document.cookie = 
  "username=Raja; expires=" + expires.toUTCString();
``

✅ Full cookie with attributes

document.cookie =
  "theme=dark; " +
  "expires=Fri, 30 Apr 2026 12:00:00 UTC; " +
  "path=/; " +
  "SameSite=Lax";

✅ 3. Read Cookies (Plain JavaScript)
❗ Important
document.cookie returns ALL cookies for the domain as a single string
Example output
username=Raja; theme=dark; language=en

✅ Read ALL cookies

console.log(document.cookie);
``

✅ Read a specific cookie (UTILITY FUNCTION)

function getCookie(name) {
  const cookies = document.cookie.split("; ");
  for (let cookie of cookies) {
    const [key, value] = cookie.split("=");
    if (key === name) {
      return value;
    }
  }
  return null;
}
Usage:

const username = getCookie("username");
console.log(username); // Raja
``

✅ 4. Update a Cookie
To update → set it again with the same name

document.cookie = "username=Reddy; path=/";
``
✅ Overwrites old value

✅ 5. Delete a Cookie
To delete → set expiry in the past
document.cookie = "username=; expires=Thu, 01 Jan 1970 00:00:00 UTC; path=/;";
✅ Cookie removed

✅ 6. Real‑World Example (Login Preference)
Set cookie

function rememberUser(name) {
  document.cookie =
    "rememberedUser=" + name +
    "; max-age=604800; path=/; SameSite=Lax";
}
Read cookie

if (getCookie("rememberedUser")) {
  console.log("Welcome back", getCookie("rememberedUser"));
}

🔐 7. What JavaScript CANNOT Do With Cookies (IMPORTANT)
❌ JS CANNOT:

document.cookie = "token=abc; HttpOnly"; // ❌ ignored
``

Feature	JS Access
HttpOnly cookies	❌ No
Secure flag	❌ JS cannot force HTTPS
Cross‑domain cookies	❌ No
✅ Only the server can set HttpOnly cookies

✅ 8. HttpOnly Cookie Example (SERVER vs JS)
Server sets cookie
Set-Cookie: refreshToken=abc123; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Lax
JS tries to read it

console.log(document.cookie);
``
Result:
❌ refreshToken NOT visible
✅ This protects against XSS attacks

⚠️ 9. Security Warnings (VERY IMPORTANT)
❌ DO NOT store:
	• JWT tokens
	• Refresh tokens
	• Sensitive user data
In JS‑accessible cookies
Why?

<script>
  alert(document.cookie); // XSS can steal cookies
</script>

✅ 10. When Should You Use JS Cookies?
Use case	OK?
Theme preference	✅ Yes
Language settings	✅ Yes
UI state	✅ Yes
Auth tokens	❌ NO
Session IDs	❌ NO

✅ 11. Cookies vs localStorage (Quick Compare)
Feature	Cookie	localStorage
Auto sent to server	✅	❌
JS access	✅	✅
HttpOnly possible	✅	❌
Size limit	~4KB	~5MB

✅ Interview‑Ready Summary (MEMORIZE)
✅ document.cookie is used to set/read cookies
✅ Cookies are stored as strings
✅ JS cannot read HttpOnly cookies
✅ Cookies sent automatically with requests
✅ Auth cookies must be HttpOnly
✅ JS cookies are for non‑sensitive data only

